Note:
Bash Emitter - Buffered output for Bash code generation

All buffer management, character/string emission, and indentation logic
is delegated to the shared byte-buffer foundation in emitter_common.runa.

Conventions:
- 2-space indentation per shell script style
- Null-terminated output strings
:End Note

Import "../emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Bash Emitter Structure (24-byte header, managed by emitter_common)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Typed mirror of the shared 24-byte emitter header so Bash-backend callers
can carry a named pointer through their code paths without referring to a
generic raw header type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three Integer fields (buffer pointer, capacity, length) at offsets 0, 8,
16 - byte-compatible with the emitter_common raw header.
@End Implementation

Type called "BashEmitter":
    buffer as Integer
    capacity as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Emitter Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Named constructor so call sites read "create_bash_emitter" rather than the
shared raw helper. Provides a single hook if Bash-specific defaults need
to diverge in the future.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_create. Returns the header pointer or 0 on
allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_bash_emitter" returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon
End Process

@Reasoning:
Paired destructor for create_bash_emitter. Returns an integer success
sentinel for use by callers that compose multiple cleanup steps.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_destroy which frees the backing buffer then the
header. Null emitter is a safe no-op returning 1.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Caller must drop the emitter pointer after this call - it becomes
dangling.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_bash_emitter" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Buffer Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lets backend code preallocate when emitting a known-large chunk (e.g. a
large heredoc) to avoid intermediate doubling churn.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_ensure_capacity which doubles capacity until the
request fits.
@End Implementation

Process called "ensure_capacity" takes emitter as Integer, needed as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_ensure_capacity from EmitterCommon with emitter, needed
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Output Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-byte append, used heavily for punctuation in Bash code emission
(`$`, `{`, `}`, `;`, etc.).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_char" takes emitter as Integer, char as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append a null-terminated string. Primary helper for variable names,
keywords, and built-in command names.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_string which measures length once and bulk
copies. Null/empty input is a no-op.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_string" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combined "emit string then newline" for line-oriented emission patterns
that dominate Bash-script generation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the string then a single LF (byte 10). Always returns 1; allocation
failures inside the underlying helpers are signalled via had_error on the
context API rather than here.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_line" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, str
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Named newline helper so the LF byte can be retuned globally without
touching call sites.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits a single LF (byte 10).
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_newline" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash tokens are space-separated; this single-space helper makes the
generator code read more naturally than literal byte-32 emits.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits a single SP (byte 32).
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_space" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash style guides standardise on 2 spaces per nesting level for control
structures (if/then/fi, while/do/done). Centralised here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops level * 2 times emitting a space byte.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(level * 2). For very deep nesting could be replaced with a precomputed
indent string.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_indent" takes emitter as Integer, level as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 2-space indentation per Bash convention.
    Let total_spaces be level multiplied by 2
    Let count be 0
    While count is less than total_spaces:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Output Retrieval
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Hand the caller a freshly allocated null-terminated copy of the buffer
contents. Called once at end-of-translation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_get_output. Caller owns the returned allocation.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Expose current write position for callers that want to compute the size
of an emitted section or to back-patch a header.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_length which reads the 8-byte length field at
offset 16 of the header.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_length" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reset length to zero so the buffer can be reused for a subsequent
translation without reallocating.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_reset which zeroes the length field. Capacity is
retained.
@End Implementation

Process called "reset" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process
